        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), ... but thou hast not been as my servant David, who kept my commandments...(cf., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and hast done worse than all who were before thee (judices nimirum et duces Israelis - Cler.), and hast gone and hast made thyself other gods (contrary to the express command in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 20:2-3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), ... and hast cast me behind thy back: therefore I bring misfortune upon the house of Jeroboam,\" etc. The expression, to cast God behind the back, which only occurs here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 23:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", denotes the most scornful contempt of God, the strict opposite of \"keeping God before the eyes and in the heart.\" בּקיר משׁתּין, every male person; see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 25:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A synonymous expression is ועזוּב עצוּר, the fettered (i.e., probably the married) and the free (or single); see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"In Israel,\" i.e., in the kingdom of the ten tribes. The threat is strengthened by the clause in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 14:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"and I will sweep out after the house of Jeroboam, as one sweepeth out dung, even to the end,\" which expresses shameful and utter extermination; and this threat is still further strengthened in ",
